1
00:00:04,942 --> 00:00:16,893
Foundation Course 2, Talk 11 The Noble Silence Buddhism without insight meditation would be like a whole system of medical theory without the medicine.

2
00:00:17,875 --> 00:00:20,957
The practice of insight vipassana has two functions.

3
00:00:21,778 --> 00:00:30,207
It begins to reveal to us a way of being in the world and in daily life and it begins to reveal a way of discovering the deepest recesses within our mind.

4
00:00:31,570 --> 00:00:35,237
Here we are concerned with finding out why this is and how it is done.

5
00:00:35,999 --> 00:00:40,487
We are going to see why intensive retreats are important to the ardent meditator.

6
00:00:42,051 --> 00:00:45,639
Again within the process of vipassana insight meditation there are two functions.

7
00:00:46,661 --> 00:00:50,287
Firstly to purify the mind and secondly to make insight.

8
00:00:51,296 --> 00:00:54,439
Both are achieved by the slow establishment of silence.

9
00:00:55,301 --> 00:01:03,450
Silence here means stillness, quietness, a situation such as a very bright, clear, windless day in which to observe the countryside.

10
00:01:04,790 --> 00:01:14,621
To make this easier for us to understand, I've drawn a diagram to suggest the human is made up of three major casings, and each casing is made up of layer upon layer.

11
00:01:16,204 --> 00:01:21,493
The first casing, the outer shell, is the personality, the outer person everyone else knows us by.

12
00:01:22,456 --> 00:01:25,221
It is the way we relate to the world, communicate with it.

13
00:01:25,781 --> 00:01:27,765
It's how we interact with people.

14
00:01:29,728 --> 00:01:36,120
In order to delve deeper into our mind, this outer circle, this casing, has to be shut down, quietened.

15
00:01:36,656 --> 00:01:42,868
This is why, when we look at the guidelines for an intensive retreat, we see people are asked to keep silent outwardly.

16
00:01:43,689 --> 00:01:47,076
There is no longer to be communication or interaction with others.

17
00:01:48,218 --> 00:01:56,775
As far as we are concerned, other people are here, on the course, as silent companions, who are dumb, deaf and blind.

18
00:01:57,768 --> 00:02:03,096
There's no need anymore even to greet people, to say hello in the morning, or to ask how they are.

19
00:02:03,716 --> 00:02:07,382
There's no need even to signal to people to let them pass on the staircase.

20
00:02:07,721 --> 00:02:10,947
One decides for oneself, either moving or waiting for the other to pass.

21
00:02:12,329 --> 00:02:15,354
At mealtimes, we eat as if no one else were in the room.

22
00:02:16,134 --> 00:02:20,942
We just let go of the usual graces of passing the salt and pouring out another's drink.

23
00:02:21,703 --> 00:02:23,284
We are learning to be alone.

24
00:02:24,105 --> 00:02:25,328
For on the journey inward...

25
00:02:25,679 --> 00:02:27,762
There will be no one to accompany us.

26
00:02:29,524 --> 00:02:34,350
People who come on a course for the first time find this very strange, even a strain.

27
00:02:35,231 --> 00:02:37,054
They feel it selfish and unnatural.

28
00:02:38,877 --> 00:02:42,581
Well, of course it is strange, but such behaviour is there for a purpose.

29
00:02:43,802 --> 00:02:46,526
When we see others are behaving in the same way, the strain will go.

30
00:02:47,609 --> 00:02:55,399
It would be selfish if it was not an agreed contract between all members of the course, but we have agreed to behave like this for the duration.

31
00:02:55,884 --> 00:02:58,907
It is unnatural, if by unnatural we mean unusual.

32
00:02:59,688 --> 00:03:04,814
But again, there are many unnatural things that have to be done in different circumstances for different purposes.

33
00:03:05,615 --> 00:03:09,038
How unnatural it is to push buttons eight hours a day or walk a tightrope.

34
00:03:10,580 --> 00:03:21,893
The purpose of this silence between meditators to the point of non-communication is because we need to shut down the outer person in order to gaze into the inner person.

35
00:03:22,479 --> 00:03:29,115
As we shall see, this takes great effort, and our energy will be dissipated if it has to go outward to people.

36
00:03:31,627 --> 00:03:35,431
This is also the reason we slow down our movements to about half pace.

37
00:03:36,354 --> 00:03:38,597
Our lives are generally full of rush and bother.

38
00:03:39,277 --> 00:03:48,250
We create great disturbances and noise by the way we go walking heavily on our feet, tramping upstairs, the way we bang doors, the way we open and close curtains.

39
00:03:49,010 --> 00:03:52,376
At mealtime we make a great crash with the knives and forks and spoons.

40
00:03:53,037 --> 00:03:57,903
Some people slurp their drink or chomp their food totally oblivious to the noise they're making.

41
00:03:58,002 --> 00:04:07,835
In other situations this might be acceptable behaviour, but on such a course as this, any noise means that the meditator is not being aware of creating silence.

42
00:04:09,075 --> 00:04:15,364
Such noise will also draw another meditator's attention, thereby distracting her from the business of looking inward.

43
00:04:16,786 --> 00:04:26,658
Especially around and in the meditation room, great effort must be made by meditators not to create even a milli-decibel of noise.

44
00:04:28,057 --> 00:04:32,641
That is why meditators are asked to move extremely slowly and deliberately.

45
00:04:33,923 --> 00:04:43,853
And this is most important in the meditation room itself, where any action, such as preparing to sit or changing posture, should be done with the quietness of a door mouse.

46
00:04:45,857 --> 00:04:49,620
Being aware of the noise we make will heighten our sense of awareness.

47
00:04:50,701 --> 00:04:55,346
Being aware of the silence we are creating will deepen our concentration.

48
00:04:55,612 --> 00:05:02,903
In this way, meditators find their meditation greatly enhanced.

49
00:05:02,923 --> 00:05:06,427
The outer person is not simply an expression of the inner person.

50
00:05:07,608 --> 00:05:09,752
It also has its own effect on the inner person.

51
00:05:10,853 --> 00:05:15,639
If we outwardly get caught up in someone's excitement, we find ourselves getting excited within us.

52
00:05:16,622 --> 00:05:20,045
If we're with someone who's depressed, often we ourselves begin to get depressed.

53
00:05:20,966 --> 00:05:22,870
Moods and emotions are infectious.

54
00:05:23,879 --> 00:05:28,384
The meditator experiences the calming of the inner person when the outer person is stilled.

55
00:05:29,187 --> 00:05:32,391
This stillness is most important on the level of morality.

56
00:05:34,113 --> 00:05:38,339
If we do harm to any being, this causes great disturbance in the mind.

57
00:05:39,360 --> 00:05:45,430
If we get angry and have an argument with someone, this causes a great fire of agitation that can take hours to die down.

58
00:05:46,951 --> 00:05:53,480
Such happenings on a course such as this would destroy the whole environment immediately, not just for the two Lizigans either.

59
00:05:53,764 --> 00:05:59,213
For this reason, all participants take on certain training rules which cut out this possibility.

60
00:06:00,656 --> 00:06:06,786
Here, within this space, all meditators should feel very safe, very secure, protected.

61
00:06:08,528 --> 00:06:14,257
How impossible it would be for us to look inward if we knew someone here was waiting for an opportunity to kill us.

62
00:06:15,278 --> 00:06:20,447
No, we have all agreed to do no harm whatsoever, not even to a bug.

63
00:06:21,202 --> 00:06:35,144
We have also agreed not to steal another's possessions, to have no sexual activity whatsoever, not to talk at all so no one can get into an argument in the first place, and finally, to take no alcohol or drugs.

64
00:06:36,045 --> 00:06:39,690
In this way, we have a basis for a very harmonious and peaceful society.

65
00:06:40,632 --> 00:06:42,254
We can rest in this environment.

66
00:06:43,416 --> 00:06:50,367
What's more, to stop causing harm to ourselves, we've taken on a rule not to eat after 12, so there's no chance of overeating.

67
00:06:51,476 --> 00:06:56,725
We've also determined not to oversleep, thereby tempting others to become lazy and waste the weekend.

68
00:06:57,706 --> 00:07:04,017
And we've determined not to disturb anyone by arousing the passions with perfumes and aftershaves, musing, dancing and hula hoops.

69
00:07:05,661 --> 00:07:09,646
So you can see this sila, morality, is vital in this sort of situation.

70
00:07:10,048 --> 00:07:17,721
It is of paramount importance if we're going to close down that outer personality and turn the energy inward to discover the inner person.

71
00:07:18,562 --> 00:07:20,024
It's very difficult at first.

72
00:07:20,365 --> 00:07:24,353
It is hard to slow down and be deliberate about everything we do.

73
00:07:25,637 --> 00:07:30,086
Even turning the handle of the door must be done with careful, slow deliberation.

74
00:07:31,288 --> 00:07:33,673
But with effort, our mindfulness will increase.

75
00:07:34,394 --> 00:07:39,404
Then, once this has been achieved, the problems of tackling the inner person can be faced.

76
00:07:42,591 --> 00:07:48,339
By this inner person I mean all the moods, emotions and feelings, all the fantasies and all the interior dialogues.

77
00:07:49,721 --> 00:07:56,230
To achieve this silence of mind we have to understand how we achieved such a busy mind in the first place.

78
00:07:57,432 --> 00:08:02,980
It was through wrong view and wrong intention that we built up a mind full of negative states.

79
00:08:04,124 --> 00:08:09,870
These negative states, for the most part, lie dormant and arise only when certain stimuli come along.

80
00:08:10,733 --> 00:08:17,281
For instance, my anger presupposes a certain disposition to react with anger when something happens.

81
00:08:18,983 --> 00:08:22,447
We've taught ourselves to get angry whenever someone disagrees with us.

82
00:08:23,709 --> 00:08:32,780
We've found this a very useful ploy, since for the most part it wins the argument for us, or at least most opponents retire frustrated if not defeated.

83
00:08:34,144 --> 00:08:37,490
Until similar occasions arise, our anger will lie dormant.

84
00:08:37,951 --> 00:08:50,652
However, as soon as we sit in meditation, just then when all stimuli have been shut down around us, just then when in a perfect circumstance of silence and support, all the anger starts coming up for no apparent reason.

85
00:08:53,235 --> 00:08:59,004
To illustrate why this is, an interesting tale is told in the scriptures of a teacher of the Dharma, who actually never meditated.

86
00:09:00,048 --> 00:09:05,918
He noticed that over a period of time, all his students became highly attained spiritually, and some even had a hat.

87
00:09:06,860 --> 00:09:08,863
He finally decided to go and seek their help.

88
00:09:09,764 --> 00:09:13,971
However, when he approached them, they'd simply say they were too busy and pass him on to another.

89
00:09:14,712 --> 00:09:18,219
The reason was that he had the sort of mind which questioned and argued.

90
00:09:18,841 --> 00:09:20,823
They presumed he'd never take their advice.

91
00:09:21,785 --> 00:09:24,890
Eventually, one of the monks asked him to approach a young boy.

92
00:09:25,816 --> 00:09:29,721
A little humbled, he nevertheless did so and asked the child how to meditate.

93
00:09:30,763 --> 00:09:37,693
The Samanera, or young novice monk, asked him how he would catch a snake he knew to be in a mound that had six exits.

94
00:09:39,196 --> 00:09:45,465
The Dharma teacher said he would do this by blocking up five exits and would simply wait patiently for the snake to come out.

95
00:09:46,285 --> 00:09:48,870
The young Samanera said exactly so.

96
00:09:49,423 --> 00:09:55,129
He pointed out to the teacher that if he wanted to observe the mind, he had to close the five senses.

97
00:09:55,710 --> 00:10:01,235
In other words, when we meditate, we are stopping the mind using its usual means of expression.

98
00:10:02,256 --> 00:10:04,619
Normally, if we are angry, we'd shout and throw something.

99
00:10:05,600 --> 00:10:07,201
It would be expressed in some way.

100
00:10:07,881 --> 00:10:17,591
But now, in the outer silence of the senses, in the stillness of the sitting posture, the mind becomes filled with its own anger and nowhere to express it.

101
00:10:18,517 --> 00:10:21,821
Suddenly, the meditator is faced with raw anger.

102
00:10:23,163 --> 00:10:32,715
Unfortunately, it's not quite as simple as it seems, for now this anger does find an outlet, and that's of course the mind itself, the sixth hole in the mound.

103
00:10:33,676 --> 00:10:38,802
The mind itself creates a dream in which anger can satisfy itself.

104
00:10:41,062 --> 00:10:42,484
There we are, sitting very still.

105
00:10:42,864 --> 00:10:46,989
To anyone coming into the meditation room, we seem so quiet, so silent.

106
00:10:47,009 --> 00:10:50,793
But internally, our minds are in a vast commotion.

107
00:10:51,313 --> 00:11:03,508
Fantasies of shouting and hitting, of slaughter and mayhem, vast battles in huge war arenas are conjured up in our minds, fueled by all the unleashed anger that can no longer find expression through the body into the world.

108
00:11:04,687 --> 00:11:14,986
even though these fantasies are not willed by the meditator, even though she finds herself caught up in them unwittingly, she is not only entertaining the anger but feeding it.

109
00:11:15,768 --> 00:11:16,429
How do we know this?

110
00:11:17,091 --> 00:11:23,302
We know this because the fantasies, if left unchecked, grow more and more violent, more and more angry.

111
00:11:23,788 --> 00:11:26,732
so that states of mind are being developed.

112
00:11:26,753 --> 00:11:38,428
Fantasies and all internal dialogues have to be vigorously noted as soon as one becomes aware of them, and the attention brought back immediately to the underlying feelings or sensations of anger in the body.

113
00:11:39,429 --> 00:11:44,397
And if these sensations are not obvious, then we must return to the process of breath.

114
00:11:46,620 --> 00:11:49,884
Now of course it's not just anger that causes this type of mental agitation.

115
00:11:50,605 --> 00:11:55,211
The Buddha in fact taught there were five causes that hindered the meditator's progress.

116
00:11:55,753 --> 00:11:59,538
They are called Nivarana and are normally translated as hindrances.

117
00:12:01,640 --> 00:12:10,873
The five hindrances to concentration are sense desire, ill will, sloth and torpor, restlessness and worry and sceptical doubt.

118
00:12:12,202 --> 00:12:17,288
When these states of mind arise, we also recognize them in the meditation for what they are.

119
00:12:18,429 --> 00:12:24,635
In a volume of smaller sayings, this is how the Buddha tells meditators how to meditate on these states of mind.

120
00:12:26,899 --> 00:12:33,546
Herein, O disciples, when some desire is present, the meditator knows there is some desire in me.

121
00:12:34,927 --> 00:12:38,750
And when desire is absent, he knows there is no sense desire in me.

122
00:12:39,777 --> 00:12:43,102
He knows how the latent sense desire comes to arise.

123
00:12:44,085 --> 00:12:46,850
He knows how to reject sense desire once it has arisen.

124
00:12:47,731 --> 00:12:51,499
And he knows how to prevent the arising of sense desire in the future.

125
00:12:53,724 --> 00:13:00,216
For sense desire, read also Ill Will, Sloth and Torpor, Restlessness and Worry, and Skeptical Doubt.

126
00:13:01,832 --> 00:13:06,019
We shall take these five in turn and see how they cover all negative states of mind.

127
00:13:06,681 --> 00:13:14,633
It's a neat classification by which the meditator can quickly recognize what state of mind he is in and so quickly decide on a course of action.

128
00:13:15,914 --> 00:13:24,769
The instructions which follow are particularly to do with Vipassana insight meditation, though they can be useful in ordinary daily life.

129
00:13:27,448 --> 00:13:31,673
It is a fact that our minds will always seek satisfaction now here and there.

130
00:13:32,475 --> 00:13:36,259
The mind always wants to be happy, excited, or at least contented.

131
00:13:37,480 --> 00:13:43,047
We have throughout our lives taught the mind to seek this happiness in pleasurable sensations that arise in the body.

132
00:13:43,927 --> 00:13:57,202
So whenever a stimulus from the outside world impinges upon the senses, be it pleasant music, a lovely scene, a cool ice cream, whatever it is, those resulting sensations is what the mind loves to indulge in, splash about in, wallow in.

133
00:13:58,211 --> 00:14:10,510
When, in the situation of an intensive meditation course, all these stimuli are taken away, the mind becomes agitated and thrashes about, looking for those sensations it has come to expect.

134
00:14:12,514 --> 00:14:22,330
The body expresses that desire with empty feelings, craving feelings, wanting feelings, just like the pangs we feel when we get a little peckish and there are no biscuits about.

135
00:14:23,575 --> 00:14:31,567
In the silence of a retreat there is no way to satisfy these demands, so the mind does a double take and tries to create them all within itself.

136
00:14:33,410 --> 00:14:38,057
Suddenly we are in cascades upon cascades of dreams, fantasies and dialogues.

137
00:14:38,077 --> 00:14:44,248
Vast epics are played out in the mind, all expressing our desire for satisfaction now here, now there.

138
00:14:45,929 --> 00:14:51,438
Sexual pleasure and erotic delight are without doubt the most delicious of sensual experiences.

139
00:14:51,908 --> 00:14:55,674
You can see its search already dominating the lives of 14 and 15 year olds.

140
00:14:57,018 --> 00:14:58,900
Our society has encouraged its indulgence.

141
00:14:59,402 --> 00:15:05,573
A whole generation and the up and coming generation are left gasping like salivating dogs at the smell of meat.

142
00:15:06,115 --> 00:15:09,782
So we as a culture stand agape before tantalizing flesh.

143
00:15:11,482 --> 00:15:16,051
Whenever you look at newspapers, billboards, virtually all films, the pleasures of sex are turned at us.

144
00:15:16,511 --> 00:15:19,918
The power of the image conditions our minds to seek these pleasures.

145
00:15:20,578 --> 00:15:26,450
And if it is reinforced with actual experience, sexual, erotic desire becomes for us a great craving and attachment.

146
00:15:27,672 --> 00:15:33,863
Should we then be so surprised that once all the avenues for its indulgence are shut, it becomes so insistent in the mind?

147
00:15:34,855 --> 00:15:38,558
I talk of sex since that is a very usual hindrance of desire.

148
00:15:39,279 --> 00:15:43,264
But others include food and drink, power and status, fame and glory.

149
00:15:43,724 --> 00:15:48,188
Indeed, any pleasure you can name can develop this obsessive quality.

150
00:15:49,350 --> 00:15:49,929
What can we do?

151
00:15:52,432 --> 00:15:56,957
In a meditation course, we are concerned to shut down the higher faculties of the mind.

152
00:15:57,899 --> 00:16:01,302
We are concerned to shut down imagination and thinking.

153
00:16:01,466 --> 00:16:07,397
When these are calmed, the intuitive mind is no longer clouded and can begin to see things as they really are.

154
00:16:08,139 --> 00:16:13,447
Therefore, our aim is to put an end to fantasy and imaginative thinking for the duration of the course.

155
00:16:14,549 --> 00:16:20,519
The most important starting point is our determination not to get caught up in them.

156
00:16:20,539 --> 00:16:25,028
This has to be a most determined decision, a most resolute resolution.

157
00:16:25,936 --> 00:16:43,416
If there is one chink in that resolution, one little teeny-weeny bit of undetermined will, if there is but one small milli-ounce of will that still wants to indulge in sensual pleasure, we can be assured that before we know it, the whole mind will be indulging, and the resolution will have been destroyed.

158
00:16:43,956 --> 00:16:46,099
The meditator becomes discouraged.

159
00:16:47,841 --> 00:16:50,203
She says she can't control her mind.

160
00:16:51,024 --> 00:16:55,149
The meditator gives up and says meditation is not for him.

161
00:16:55,702 --> 00:16:59,471
Our wills must be steeled against sensual indulgence.

162
00:16:59,490 --> 00:17:05,502
In this way, as soon as there is so much as a tickle, the attention will be immediately drawn to it.

163
00:17:06,203 --> 00:17:11,714
As soon as the meditator is aware of it and remains aware of it, noting it, it will begin to pass away.

164
00:17:14,160 --> 00:17:16,986
This is an important point to grasp.

165
00:17:17,641 --> 00:17:27,032
When a thought arises out of the subconscious, say a sudden picture of cheese, that image is immediately grasped by desire, our conditioned states of mind, the sankara.

166
00:17:28,095 --> 00:17:33,320
Energy is put into it, and the whole higher mind becomes engaged in developing that initial image.

167
00:17:34,522 --> 00:17:41,471
And so the powers of imaginative thinking will go into creating a huge banquet around the initial image of cheese.

168
00:17:42,650 --> 00:17:51,479
The meditator, who has made that resolute resolution, who is ardent and energetic, will catch that fantasy at birth, that first image.

169
00:17:52,700 --> 00:17:55,823
In so doing, he preempts the conditioning to develop it.

170
00:17:56,804 --> 00:18:01,268
He gets between the desired image and the desiring attachment.

171
00:18:01,288 --> 00:18:08,255
This stops, this calms the higher mind, and the awareness can then gaze intelligently and energetically at the object.

172
00:18:10,396 --> 00:18:11,137
The higher mind

173
00:18:11,489 --> 00:18:19,060
can be engaged in naming it, in labeling it, but that distance of the objective observer must be kept inviolate.

174
00:18:20,142 --> 00:18:25,651
The object, the image of cheese, has been produced by latent energy in the subconscious.

175
00:18:25,671 --> 00:18:26,531
It needs fuel.

176
00:18:27,053 --> 00:18:30,718
It needs the higher mind to develop it, or it will simply lose energy.

177
00:18:31,559 --> 00:18:37,669
To the meditator's delight, as she gazes, observes this image intently, it passes, it just fades away.

178
00:18:37,969 --> 00:18:39,791
Most times it just vanishes.

179
00:18:40,108 --> 00:18:47,640
She is left with feelings in the body which are then more easily observed just as the sensations caused by the breath process are observed.

180
00:18:49,742 --> 00:18:53,848
Here then is how we tackle sensual desire in Vipassana Insight Meditation.

181
00:18:54,829 --> 00:18:59,897
We determine with an unshakable active resolution not to get caught up in sense pleasure.

182
00:19:01,038 --> 00:19:06,386
We determine with an unshakable resolute resolution to be awake, alert like a sentinel.

183
00:19:07,057 --> 00:19:19,739
As soon as any pleasing image or feeling arises, the meditator zaps it with alert, keen, intelligent awareness and stays with it, regarding it as a scientist, with objectivity, until it passes away.

184
00:19:20,500 --> 00:19:22,242
Then, back to the breath process.

185
00:19:24,686 --> 00:19:32,339
As with sensual desire, so also with other images, thoughts and feelings concerning the whole area of ill-will and aversion.

186
00:19:33,349 --> 00:19:49,045
images of people and things we dislike, grudging dialogues where we never forgive the insult or the harm done, the great battles and wars fought to death inspired by revenge, scenes of cruelty and inflicted suffering on our enemies and rivals.

187
00:19:50,365 --> 00:19:55,871
All these, like desire, give the mind great satisfaction, for the mind wants to indulge its ill will.

188
00:19:56,592 --> 00:19:59,173
There is relief to be had in letting off steam.

189
00:19:59,575 --> 00:20:02,057
There's pleasure to be had in revenge and cruelty.

190
00:20:02,762 --> 00:20:13,104
But with the same technique of alert, keen awareness, we catch these movements of aversion in the mind, snip them quickly in the bud, and know them to be aversion and ill-will.

191
00:20:14,026 --> 00:20:18,295
Know them to be harmful and observe them intently and equanimously.

192
00:20:19,036 --> 00:20:23,826
We must become the objective observers of the mind's ill-will and aversion.

193
00:20:26,522 --> 00:20:35,416
One of my meditation teachers, the Venerable Ujjanaka, used to call the third hindrance, sloth and torpor, the meditators' two very good friends.

194
00:20:36,999 --> 00:20:38,642
And that's just how they present themselves.

195
00:20:39,182 --> 00:20:42,027
They are very clever, full of subtle argument and pretense.

196
00:20:42,627 --> 00:20:48,717
But we must beware, for they are fifth columnists, traitors, and will sell us out to the enemy.

197
00:20:49,117 --> 00:20:50,420
They tell us, we're tired.

198
00:20:50,920 --> 00:20:52,061
We've worked hard enough.

199
00:20:52,722 --> 00:20:53,663
There's no more energy.

200
00:20:53,703 --> 00:20:55,467
It's too much, too much suffering.

201
00:20:55,967 --> 00:20:57,328
No one has suffered like me.

202
00:20:57,849 --> 00:20:58,991
It's time to rest now.

203
00:20:59,853 --> 00:21:00,953
Ah, sleep, sleep.

204
00:21:01,034 --> 00:21:01,674
You've earned it.

205
00:21:01,996 --> 00:21:03,817
Just a little rest, just five minutes, that's all.

206
00:21:04,038 --> 00:21:04,778
What's five minutes?

207
00:21:04,960 --> 00:21:06,161
And we'll wake up so refreshed.

208
00:21:06,422 --> 00:21:07,222
Go on, that's it.

209
00:21:07,462 --> 00:21:08,223
Just lie down.

210
00:21:08,664 --> 00:21:11,489
Rest just a moment.

211
00:21:11,509 --> 00:21:12,170
Ah, and we've gone.

212
00:21:13,191 --> 00:21:18,298
Five minutes, 16 minutes, one hour, two hours, three hours, and we wake.

213
00:21:18,598 --> 00:21:20,019
And we know we've been duped.

214
00:21:21,521 --> 00:21:23,624
No, we've fooled ourselves.

215
00:21:26,626 --> 00:21:30,951
As very small children, we're often taught to find the end of our problems in sleep.

216
00:21:31,833 --> 00:21:37,939
When their children are irritable or weepy, or making a lot of noise, parents will say, they're tired, they need sleep.

217
00:21:38,880 --> 00:21:43,545
Now maybe they do, but often it's an excuse for putting the kids to bed and out of the way.

218
00:21:44,425 --> 00:21:48,150
Either way, the children learn to overcome difficulties by zonking out.

219
00:21:48,771 --> 00:21:50,673
Of course, one does wake refreshed.

220
00:21:51,193 --> 00:21:53,596
Sometimes sleeping on a problem does help.

221
00:21:53,615 --> 00:21:56,598
The mind has subconscious ways of dealing with such things.

222
00:21:56,618 --> 00:21:59,882
But often, sleep is an indulgence, the Sunday lie-in.

223
00:22:00,501 --> 00:22:04,205
The whole day in bed with newspapers, plus trays of food and videos.

224
00:22:05,467 --> 00:22:10,451
But here, on our Vipassana Insight meditation course, the indulgence in sleep is a destructor.

225
00:22:11,332 --> 00:22:14,295
For sleep saps our energy and leaves us groggy.

226
00:22:14,974 --> 00:22:16,737
Our wills in tatters.

227
00:22:17,070 --> 00:22:20,576
Our bodies work according to what is known as the circadian cycle.

228
00:22:21,497 --> 00:22:24,181
If this cycle is disturbed, we feel terrible.

229
00:22:25,221 --> 00:22:28,205
This is what happens in international flights and causes jet lag.

230
00:22:29,188 --> 00:22:30,670
Our sleep rhythms are disturbed.

231
00:22:31,550 --> 00:22:42,605
When we wake at the end of a sleep sequence and indulge it in another hour or two, we unwittingly set up another cycle of sleep and we will feel groggy until it has been completed.

232
00:22:43,700 --> 00:22:49,473
The cycles vary in individuals from as little as 5 hours for adults to 12 or 13 hours for young children.

233
00:22:50,375 --> 00:23:00,560
Here, of course, we have to beware not to start a cycle, or else this whole weekend meditation becomes an intensive, sleeping meditation course.

234
00:23:02,988 --> 00:23:08,794
Now all this has to be tempered by the fact that many of us live highly pressured lives, full of stress and worry.

235
00:23:09,595 --> 00:23:17,384
This takes its toll on our bodies and minds, and on a weekend course the whole Saturday can feel terrible, depending on what state of mind we've come with.

236
00:23:18,585 --> 00:23:26,733
But we still have to make sure that if we are going to sleep during the rest periods, that it is a real tiredness and not laziness.

237
00:23:27,490 --> 00:23:32,815
not the listlessness of depression, not a conditioned reaction to suffering, to boredom.

238
00:23:34,536 --> 00:23:41,902
The Buddha, again in the shorter sayings, gives advice to his great disciple Moggallana, who became an adept in all the great powers.

239
00:23:42,903 --> 00:23:46,625
He suggests six ways of overcoming sleepiness before deciding to lie down.

240
00:23:47,346 --> 00:23:56,535
Firstly, he says, not to dwell on it, not to give it attention, that is, to keep the mind on the process of breath, raising energy into the observation.

241
00:23:56,515 --> 00:24:05,450
If this doesn't work, the meditator should think about how harmful sloth and torpor is and recall to mind the effects they know of and then go back to the breath.

242
00:24:06,951 --> 00:24:12,521
The next is to repeat whatever doctrine one knows off by heart till the sloth is dispelled.

243
00:24:13,303 --> 00:24:18,692
If this doesn't work, the Buddha advises us to rub our ears and limbs with the palms of our hands.

244
00:24:20,900 --> 00:24:25,346
Then the Buddha advises that if this fails, we should splash water over our faces.

245
00:24:25,948 --> 00:24:27,990
If that fails, we should walk up and down.

246
00:24:28,692 --> 00:24:33,420
At the end of all this effort, to stay awake, if tiredness still overcomes us, then we should lie down.

247
00:24:34,020 --> 00:24:45,117
But mindfully, and he goes on, having awakened, you should rise quickly, thinking, I won't indulge in the enjoyment of lying down and reclining, in the enjoyment of sleep.

248
00:24:47,173 --> 00:24:52,902
So what the Buddha wants us to do is to be aware of not giving in to tiredness.

249
00:24:54,083 --> 00:24:58,249
We have to test it in the context of our particular insight meditation practice.

250
00:24:59,391 --> 00:25:02,013
We can firstly try to put energy into observing.

251
00:25:02,474 --> 00:25:06,580
If that fails, we can rise and stretch ourselves slowly and silently.

252
00:25:07,382 --> 00:25:09,904
If that fails, we can do walking meditation.

253
00:25:10,866 --> 00:25:16,354
But if tiredness still seems to overcome us, then we can lie down with a determination to wake mindfully.

254
00:25:17,936 --> 00:25:21,865
In longer courses, meditators always experience a loss of demand for sleep.

255
00:25:22,666 --> 00:25:25,673
Often, the first day or two is nothing but sloth and torpor.

256
00:25:26,295 --> 00:25:32,970
But then, because of the power of awareness and its purifying effects, sleep time drops to six hours and sometimes to four.

257
00:25:33,951 --> 00:25:37,278
Even in a week-long course, some meditators do without a night's sleep.

258
00:25:39,502 --> 00:25:45,329
The difference between sloth and torpor is that sloth is felt in the body and torpor is felt in the mind.

259
00:25:46,270 --> 00:25:49,816
Often meditators experience torpor like a heavy cloud on the mind.

260
00:25:50,336 --> 00:25:54,662
Again, it is a matter of observing it and returning to the process of breath.

261
00:25:55,442 --> 00:25:59,468
But if one feels overcome by it, then walking meditation is the best answer.

262
00:26:02,372 --> 00:26:06,777
Restlessness and worry, agitation and anxiety are the fourth hindrance.

263
00:26:07,903 --> 00:26:13,972
When we sit for some time, even if we begin in a calm way, a feeling can arise to get up to move.

264
00:26:14,653 --> 00:26:15,434
We get fidgety.

265
00:26:16,115 --> 00:26:17,557
We start thinking about the time.

266
00:26:18,238 --> 00:26:19,800
Is the half hour or hour up yet?

267
00:26:20,442 --> 00:26:21,323
Maybe I've missed the bell.

268
00:26:22,865 --> 00:26:25,848
This restlessness can be caused by any reason.

269
00:26:27,070 --> 00:26:30,756
It might be some worry, real or imagined, that keeps coming up in the mind.

270
00:26:31,157 --> 00:26:38,265
It might be a lot of unresolved feelings which are all repressed and unknown to the meditator but cause such agitation in the mind and body.

271
00:26:39,546 --> 00:26:42,689
In meditation the causes of such things are not important.

272
00:26:43,470 --> 00:26:46,712
We have to deal directly with the presenting problem.

273
00:26:48,173 --> 00:26:57,502
When restlessness comes we must raise our determination to sit still till it has passed or until the time allotted to the meditation is finished.

274
00:26:57,938 --> 00:27:04,407
Here, unlike sloth and torpor, the energy is high, but it's fractured and bursting out all over the place.

275
00:27:05,410 --> 00:27:08,694
So our determination is placed into focusing the energy.

276
00:27:09,936 --> 00:27:15,946
When restlessness arises, we're much more concerned to sharpen the concentration and establish equanimity.

277
00:27:16,888 --> 00:27:44,971
to sharpen the concentration we can rest the attention on the breath and whenever restlessness claims our attention we simply note it vigorously so as not to let it affect our thinking and our will to remain remember the work of a meditator is to see things objectively when the restlessness is observed it is done as by a stranger in an art gallery or museum the restlessness manifests in the body

278
00:27:45,137 --> 00:27:47,480
is seen and observed as something other.

279
00:27:48,541 --> 00:27:50,063
The awareness keeps its distance.

280
00:27:50,963 --> 00:28:09,343
If there is ever a feeling that the restlessness is getting the better of us, if its suggestions to get up to finish cause us to make even the slightest movement of a finger or an eyelid, then we must take refuge in the breath process, bringing the concentration to bear until we have re-established our equanimity.

281
00:28:10,544 --> 00:28:14,048
It is very important in this practice to overcome restlessness.

282
00:28:14,196 --> 00:28:18,584
If we give in, the next time is always that little bit harder to resist.

283
00:28:19,565 --> 00:28:28,078
If we are patient and wait until the restlessness begins to subside or even pass altogether, the next time will be that much easier.

284
00:28:30,782 --> 00:28:33,386
Finally, there is sceptical doubt.

285
00:28:33,805 --> 00:28:36,368
Now this can be quite a disease with some people.

286
00:28:37,130 --> 00:28:40,994
The Buddha said the skeptic was the least able to make spiritual progress.

287
00:28:41,615 --> 00:28:44,660
The reason is that a person who doubts never moves.

288
00:28:45,942 --> 00:28:50,028
If I doubt whether I can dive off the top board as a swimming pool, I'll never do it.

289
00:28:50,909 --> 00:28:53,873
If I doubt my doctor's ability, I won't take the medicine.

290
00:28:54,950 --> 00:28:57,532
As a hindrance to insight, there are three types of doubt.

291
00:28:58,413 --> 00:29:02,958
First, there is the doubt in the Buddha and what he taught, the Dharma.

292
00:29:02,978 --> 00:29:04,019
Was he really enlightened?

293
00:29:04,740 --> 00:29:05,740
What does that mean anyway?

294
00:29:06,461 --> 00:29:09,184
How do I know he wasn't really as deluded as all of us?

295
00:29:10,066 --> 00:29:11,606
This Nibbana is probably a hoax.

296
00:29:11,948 --> 00:29:13,169
It's just annihilation or something.

297
00:29:14,630 --> 00:29:16,392
Then there's doubt in the meditation teacher.

298
00:29:17,413 --> 00:29:19,434
Well, how much does he know?

299
00:29:20,215 --> 00:29:21,877
How do I know he knows anything at all?

300
00:29:22,298 --> 00:29:23,859
He doesn't look saintly to me.

301
00:29:24,682 --> 00:29:26,085
She doesn't look enlightened at all.

302
00:29:26,826 --> 00:29:28,229
Maybe she's just on an ego trip.

303
00:29:29,770 --> 00:29:31,133
Finally, there's doubting oneself.

304
00:29:31,693 --> 00:29:33,717
Yes, the Buddha was certainly enlightened.

305
00:29:33,856 --> 00:29:34,778
I've no doubt about that.

306
00:29:34,798 --> 00:29:35,900
The teacher's very good.

307
00:29:35,961 --> 00:29:36,902
She knows what she's doing.

308
00:29:36,922 --> 00:29:37,903
She's an excellent teacher.

309
00:29:38,263 --> 00:29:38,944
He's very fair.

310
00:29:39,025 --> 00:29:39,705
I understand him.

311
00:29:40,287 --> 00:29:40,768
It's me.

312
00:29:41,528 --> 00:29:42,150
I'm not up to it.

313
00:29:42,269 --> 00:29:43,092
I can't do it.

314
00:29:43,612 --> 00:29:47,198
I don't have the perfections, the necessary ability to achieve anything.

315
00:29:49,117 --> 00:29:58,393
To undercut these sorts of doubts, that is why, of course, at the beginning of the weekend course we always take refuge in the Buddha Dhamma Sangha, the Triple Gem.

316
00:29:59,394 --> 00:30:02,920
It's important to build up trust, to build confidence in the Triple Gem.

317
00:30:04,182 --> 00:30:13,336
This just means that a meditator will give it a go, that there will be a complete dedication to the task in hand, a steadiness of commitment.

318
00:30:14,161 --> 00:30:20,857
Over such a short period as a weekend course, all that is asked is a total self-giving just for that period of time.

319
00:30:21,519 --> 00:30:27,493
In this way, after the weekend, a person can judge whether in fact there is anything to be gained from this meditation.

320
00:30:28,737 --> 00:30:31,123
We can think about it after the experience.

321
00:30:32,115 --> 00:30:36,923
If we don't lend ourselves totally to the experience, we'll never know whether it really works or not.

322
00:30:37,763 --> 00:30:43,993
It wouldn't be fair to oneself to give something a half-hearted go and then say, well, I didn't get much out of that.

323
00:30:45,134 --> 00:30:54,849
By committing oneself totally to this meditation practice for a period of time, after that period, a meditator can look back and ask whether in fact there was any benefit.

324
00:30:57,242 --> 00:31:02,891
If a person suffers from overweight and goes to a health farm, he doesn't go there with his own set of conditions.

325
00:31:03,231 --> 00:31:04,333
He'll follow the regime.

326
00:31:05,515 --> 00:31:11,683
Going to a health farm demands a certain surrendering to the system, allowing the system to work itself on the person.

327
00:31:12,925 --> 00:31:13,646
It's not horrific.

328
00:31:15,009 --> 00:31:19,675
The person has read about such farms, has had friends who have gone there and praised the place and so on.

329
00:31:21,077 --> 00:31:23,622
He knows generally what to expect.

330
00:31:23,804 --> 00:31:24,785
and it doesn't last forever.

331
00:31:25,204 --> 00:31:28,949
He goes on trial for a serious, dedicated, energetic trial.

332
00:31:30,069 --> 00:31:36,037
It is in this way we can overcome skeptical doubt in our meditation practice and on such a course as this.

333
00:31:37,718 --> 00:31:44,325
We dismiss all doubt, push it gently to the side and dedicate ourselves to the practicing of the technique.

334
00:31:45,645 --> 00:31:49,170
After we've gone through the ordeal, then we can look back and judge.

335
00:31:50,145 --> 00:31:54,506
If we have gained nothing, then at least we've cleared out one venue of exploration.

336
00:31:55,008 --> 00:31:58,704
Now we know Vipassana Insight Meditation is not for us.

337
00:32:00,067 --> 00:32:06,616
We have to be so careful not to waste precious time getting caught up in all that internal argumentation.

338
00:32:07,438 --> 00:32:09,701
Voice 1 saying, let's go, this is silly.

339
00:32:10,342 --> 00:32:13,145
Voice 2 saying, no, let's stay, it's interesting.

340
00:32:13,606 --> 00:32:15,869
Voice 3 saying, this is all very dangerous.

341
00:32:16,371 --> 00:32:18,513
Voice 4, what is all this Buddhist stuff anyway?

342
00:32:18,894 --> 00:32:21,637
Voice 5, we should have gone to see that film.

343
00:32:21,617 --> 00:32:30,929
Doubt creates great splits in the mind, and all the emotions of fear, frustration, depression, and so on are conjured up, all adding fuel with voice upon voice.

344
00:32:32,310 --> 00:32:34,353
We get caught up in views and opinions.

345
00:32:34,773 --> 00:32:41,821
We lose the balance of our minds and become more and more confused by the arguments, raging on and on until we give up in despair.

346
00:32:42,522 --> 00:32:43,443
I'll never know the truth.

347
00:32:44,244 --> 00:32:45,205
The truth can't be known.

348
00:32:46,106 --> 00:32:47,568
Or we end up in cold dismissiveness.

349
00:32:48,009 --> 00:32:48,789
It's all rubbish.

350
00:32:50,692 --> 00:32:56,509
This hindrance of sceptical doubt is easily undermined by raising confidence in the triple gem, the teacher and oneself.

351
00:32:57,250 --> 00:32:59,215
Remember, faith is not belief.

352
00:32:59,917 --> 00:33:01,682
The Buddha didn't ask us to believe him.

353
00:33:02,104 --> 00:33:04,872
He just said, come and try, see if it works.

354
00:33:05,205 --> 00:33:08,069
When skeptical doubt arises in the mind, just smile.

355
00:33:08,611 --> 00:33:09,992
Brush it gently to the side.

356
00:33:10,433 --> 00:33:14,380
Say to yourself that you will deal with all these worries after the course.

357
00:33:14,900 --> 00:33:18,546
Remind yourself that all doubt is dispelled through experience.

358
00:33:19,086 --> 00:33:23,492
For what is the root cause of all our doubting if it is not ignorance?

359
00:33:23,512 --> 00:33:24,894
We don't actually know.

360
00:33:25,476 --> 00:33:27,098
We're afraid of our unknowing.

361
00:33:27,720 --> 00:33:30,083
When we know, there is no doubt.

362
00:33:30,333 --> 00:33:34,758
I can spend a whole lifetime worrying and doubting whether I can dive off the top board or not.

363
00:33:35,298 --> 00:33:38,942
But when I experience it, when I do it, what happens to the doubt?

364
00:33:40,525 --> 00:33:41,807
Doubt is a great conjurer.

365
00:33:42,627 --> 00:33:45,131
We must determine not to get caught up in its tricks.

366
00:33:45,730 --> 00:33:48,775
We must determine to put our effort into the practice.

367
00:33:51,538 --> 00:33:57,285
So there we have the five hindrances, the Nivarana, which creates so much bother and commotion within the inner person.

368
00:33:58,446 --> 00:34:01,971
The Buddha likened this mind to a pot of water.

369
00:34:03,553 --> 00:34:08,239
When the water is mixed with different colors, it is like a mind possessed with sensual desire.

370
00:34:10,041 --> 00:34:13,005
A person looking into it cannot properly recognize their own face.

371
00:34:14,246 --> 00:34:17,251
When the pot is boiling and bubbling, it's like a mind filled with anger.

372
00:34:17,931 --> 00:34:23,137
When the water is covered with moss and water plants, it's like a mind overcome with sloth and torpor.

373
00:34:24,264 --> 00:34:29,690
When the water is stirred and agitated by the wind, it is like a mind overcome with restlessness and worry.

374
00:34:30,570 --> 00:34:35,295
When the water has become turbid and muddy, it is like a mind overcome with doubt.

375
00:34:36,717 --> 00:34:42,702
In all cases, when a person looks into such a pot, he will not recognize or see the image of his own face.

376
00:34:44,065 --> 00:34:48,228
When we are overcome by these hindrances, we cannot see things as they really are.

377
00:34:48,769 --> 00:34:49,851
We are deluded by them.

378
00:34:50,851 --> 00:34:54,255
Although these hindrances do not entirely disappear till full...

